tIV. Thessalian -- tSome Materials for a Historical Grammar of the Thessalian Dialect -- tPalatalized Consonants in Thessalian? New Perspectives on an Old Problem -- tThessalian Secondary 3pl. -(ι)εν and the Optative: Dangerous Liaisons -- tMore on Aspect and Modality in Thessalian Official Documents -- tOn Thessalian πόκκι Constructions: A Morphosyntactic and Semantic Question -- tV. Lesbian -- tLesbian and Mainland Greece -- tRené Hodot Lesbian, in Space, Time, and its Uses -- tVI. North Ionic And The Black Sea -- tThe Ionic of North Aegean (from the River Strymon to the River Hebrus) -- tThe Greek Language in the Black Sea -- tThe Dialect of Thasos and the Transmission of Archilochus’ Fragments -- tIndex locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new collective volume with over twenty important studies on less well-studied dialects of ancient Greek, particularly of the northern regions. The book covers geographically a broad area of the classical Greek world ranging from Central Greece to the overseas Greek colonies of Thrace and the Black Sea. Particular emphasis is placed on the epichoric varieties of areas on the northern fringe of the classical Greek world, including Thessaly, Epirus and Macedonia. Recent advances in research are taken into consideration in providing state-of-the art accounts of these understudied dialects, but also of more well-known dialects like Lesbian. In addition, other papers address special intriguing topics in these, but also in other dialects, such as Thessalian, Lesbian and Ionic, or focus on important multi-dialectal corpora such as the oracular tablets from Dodona. Finally, a number of studies examine broader topics like the supraregional Doric koinai or the concept of dialect continuum, or even explore the possibility of an ancient Balkansprachbund, which included Greek too. This new reference work covers a gap in current research and will be indispensable for people interested in Greek dialectology and ancient Greek in general.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGreek languagexDialectsvCongresses. 4aAntike (Griechenland). 4aDialektologie. 4akoine. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Greek.  adialectology.  akoine.1 aBarrio Vega, María Luisa del, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBubenik, Vit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCassio, Albio Cesare, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrespo, Emilio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrespo, Emilio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDosuna, Julián Méndez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDéniz, Alcorac Alonso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilos, Panagiotis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFilos, Panagiotis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFinkelberg, Margalit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiannakis, Georgios K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiannakis, Georgios K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHatzopoulos, Miltiades B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHelly, Bruno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIzquierdo, Enrique Nieto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanko, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Brian D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/